RABIES - INDONESIA: (BALI) MONKEY, HUMAN EXPOSURE SUSPECTED
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 10 Dec 2016
Source: The Sunday Telegraph [edited]
http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/australian-tourist-laura-hawkins-was-bitten-by-a-monkey-while-holidaying-in-bali/news-story/9640cc7aa6085ae572165e7852703062


Travel agent LH used to encourage people to experience the monkey temples in Asia -- until she was bitten by monkeys in Bali and faced a terrifying wait to see if she had rabies.

She is one of an increasing number of tourists exposed to the deadly rabies virus.

"I was feeding the monkeys bananas and I ran out of food and one monkey wasn't happy about that and just grabbed my hand and bit me," the 29-year-old from Tweed Heads [New South Wales/NSW] said.

They're cute, but can be dangerous too.

"The 1st thing I thought was rabies and 'oh my God, I haven't had the rabies vaccination'. "I flew home that night and went straight to the Tweed Heads hospital."

LH began the month-long treatment that required weekly injections of the vaccine and infusions of immunoglobulin before being cleared of rabies [see Australian PEP recommendations below in the comment. - Mod.LM]

Now she cautions travellers about the dangers.

Australia is one of the few countries without rabies but the deadly virus is right on our doorstep. More than 300 travellers from NSW were exposed to rabies after an animal bite in 2015.

The vaccine costs AUD 300 [about USD 225].

Monkey and dog bites were the most common and all 303 people who were bitten required immediate post exposure rabies vaccine on their return to Australia.

[Byline: Jane Hansen]

